    <h2>EC Search on Reginet: Detailed Process</h2>
    <p>The EC search on <strong>Reginet</strong> is the most important tool for property buyers. Here is the detailed search process: Navigate to the TNREGINET homepage and click on the "Encumbrance Certificate" section. Select the search type — EC search by survey number is standard for land parcels. Choose the district from the dropdown. Choose the SRO from the list (the SRO name corresponds to the area where the property is located). Select the village from the dropdown. Enter the survey number and subdivision number if applicable. For layout plots, switch to the plot search mode and enter the layout name, plot number, and street name. Define the search period by selecting the start year and end year. Click on the "Search" button. The system queries the TNREGINET database and returns a list of all transactions registered for the property in the specified period. You can view each transaction\'s details, including deed type, date, parties, and property description. Downloading a copy of the results for reference and cross-checking via <a href="/tn-ec/">TN EC</a> completes the initial due-diligence process.</p>

    <h2>Guideline Value on Reginet</h2>
    <p>One of the most practical tools on <strong>Reginet</strong> is the guideline value search. This feature lets property buyers check the government-approved minimum per-square-foot or per-hectare valuation rate for any street or survey number in Tamil Nadu before proceeding with a sale or mortgage. The guideline value search requires users to enter the district, taluk, village, survey number, and the year for which they want to check the rate. The portal displays the applicable rate, the property classification (residential, commercial, agricultural), and the effective date of the current rate. This value is critical for calculating stamp duty accurately. Undervaluing a property in the sale deed relative to the guideline value triggers a Section 47A inquiry and can delay registration. Buyers must cross-reference the guideline value with the agreed sale price and calculate the stamp duty accordingly.</p>

